the dead to the living. For instance, all must grapple with complex yet contradictory clinical assertions of death as easily detectable and absolute; nevertheless, transplants are regularly celebrated as forms of rebirth, and donors as living on in others' bodies. New forms of sociality arise, too: recipients and donors' relatives may defy sanctions against communication, and through personal encounters strangers are transformed into kin. Sharp also considers current experimental research efforts to develop alternative sources for human parts, with prototypes ranging from genetically altered animals to sophisticated mechanical devices. These future trajectories generate intriguing responses among both scientists and transplant recipients as they consider how such alternatives might reshape established-yet unusual-forms of embodied intimacy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aAnthropologie médicalexÉtats-Unis. 0aDeathxUnited States. 0aDeathzUnited States. 0aDeuilxCoutumesxÉtats-Unis. 0aEthnologiexÉtats-Unis. 0aEthnologyxUnited States. 0aEthnologyzUnited States. 0aFuneral rites and ceremoniesxUnited States. 0aFuneral rites and ceremonieszUnited States. 0aFunéraillesxRites et cérémoniesxÉtats-Unis. 0aGreffe (Chirurgie)xAspect socialxÉtats-Unis. 0aKinshipxUnited States. 0aKinshipzUnited States. 0aMedical anthropologyxUnited States. 0aMedical anthropologyzUnited States. 0aMemorialsxUnited States. 0aMemorialszUnited States. 0aMonuments commémoratifsxÉtats-Unis. 0aMortxÉtats-Unis. 0aMourning customsxUnited States. 0aMourning customszUnited States. 0aParentéxÉtats-Unis. 0aTransplantation of organs, tissues, etcxSocial aspectsxUnited States. 0aTransplantation of organs, tissues, etcxSocial aspectszUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2